the events of today will be history. I still recall in 1920, when I was in the
fifth grade, the feeling of wonder and shock with which we learned that the

00:20.660 --> 00:29.760
eighth graders upstairs were studying World War II from their history books. How
could something we had just lived through be history? And I understand that

00:29.760 --> 00:41.140
there are people today feeling the same shock at finding that the 60s are any
story of this. Well, out of the wisdom thus learned, I wish to give you this

00:41.140 --> 00:50.700
cassette of thoughts and statements of very recently. Mostly they are thoughts I
presented at meetings of the Little Men's, which is to say the elves, gnomes,

00:50.760 --> 01:00.000
leprechauns, and little men's chowder, marching, and science fiction society,
the source of the Invisible Little Men Award. The organization was named after

01:00.000 --> 01:09.560
the social club to which belonged Mr. O'Malley, Barnaby's fairy godfather, in
the comic strip by Cockett Johnson in the days between World War II and

01:09.560 --> 01:19.760
McCarthyism. It ended then because Johnson was reported to have had a communist
class. In the earliest days, the little man published the Rotomagnetic Digest,

01:19.920 --> 01:28.200
of which, I have been told, at least one complete set was still extant as
recently as a year or two ago. But I wasn't one of the little men at that time.

01:28.500 --> 01:37.400
These thoughts are much more recent. There was the time, for instance, that I
reviewed Poul Anderson's Home Brew, a collection of excellent short pieces of

01:37.400 --> 01:47.000
which perhaps the most brilliant is Uncleavie's True Thinking, in which he
translates atomic theory into English. I had occasion to comment on his

01:47.000 --> 01:57.020
characterization of fascism on page 28 of the book. I noted that anyone living
today should know that the packaging is not the contents and that the sales

01:57.020 --> 02:06.480
pitch is not the product. Furthermore, we do know what fascism is. Just as
communism as attempts of people living under fewer regimes to move towards

02:06.480 --> 02:16.500
democracy and industrialization, fascism is an effort to stop a people's moves
into democracy and to move them back to a medieval society. Of course, neither

02:16.500 --> 02:27.120
effort can be fully successful. Shortly after reviewing the book The Early Long,
I had occasion to mention my earliest memory of a work by C. L. Moore. Since

02:27.120 --> 02:33.260
much of The Earliest Long and The Earliest More both appeared in Weird Tales,
this was entirely appropriate.

02:35.880 --> 02:47.380
Those of you who have read The Early Long may remember that the earliest long
was fairly representative of the usual contents of weird tales. No evoking of

02:47.380 --> 02:56.800
weirdness or horror, just an assertion of it. No real description, just an
assertion of indescribableness. A heavy reliance on slime and filth and stench

02:56.800 --> 03:05.980
and immobilization. The murkiest of background hidden with the murkiest of
prose. But don't get the idea that all of it was like that. There was some

03:05.980 --> 03:16.540
action prose and some true description. For me, the high point of that came in
September of 1934. The East Bay Scientific Association was the local branch of

03:16.540 --> 03:26.080
the World Fan Organization, the International Scientific Association. We met at
Aubrey McDermott's house that month, in fact, most months. My copy of Weird

03:26.080 --> 03:36.460
Tales hadn't come yet, but Aubrey's had. He handed it to me, opened, and said,
Read that story. So I read it to him. It was so perfectly written that it simply

03:36.460 --> 03:46.500
flowed with no effort on my part. it was a beautifully clean prose everything
was simply told clear and clean description just told what happened what the

03:46.500 --> 03:55.080
characters did and said and what happened to them and how they destroyed each
other it was a tale of how a defeated warrior woman escaped from the dungeon of

03:55.080 --> 04:04.580
her conquered castle went down a hole in its lowest level and found there a
world with a power which she came back and used when i finished the members

04:04.580 --> 04:14.060
thought i had been rehearsing to read it so well but i'd never seen it before it
was simply that good a job of writing the writer was C. O. Moore the story was the

04:14.060 --> 04:25.760
black god's kiss it's now in print in the best of C. O. Moore another note i found
in my archives is undated and also takes off from a passage written by Poul i

04:25.760 --> 04:32.600
probably never before mentioned it to anyone but because i have used it to
comment on the nature of science fiction it's worth recording.

04:33.920 --> 04:38.540
Poul writes that it has been said that those who do not learn history must repeat it.

04:39.360 --> 04:44.780
Ben Bova in another magazine published a little sooner, wrote that, to paraphrase Santayana,

04:45.280 --> 04:48.780
those who ignore the lessons of history are doomed to repeat the mistakes.

04:49.740 --> 04:50.940
I remember both endings.

04:51.660 --> 04:57.400
The both of my versions say that those who do not or was it refused to learn from history

04:57.400 --> 04:59.680
are condemned to, et cetera.

05:00.940 --> 05:09.880
There is considerable difference of content here. It makes little
difference whether we must or are condemned or are doomed, but it matters much

05:09.880 --> 05:18.300
whether we need to learn history or to learn from it, and whether history has
lessons we must learn or simply contents from which we must draw our own

05:18.300 --> 05:29.360
learnings. Another instructor in my department has been known to ask his student
why truth is better told by myths than by factual instruction, and this has

05:29.360 --> 05:38.720
relevance here. It is noteworthy that the truths learned from history are never
embodied in our histories, but in our mythologies, which often then are

05:38.720 --> 05:51.520
reabsorbed into the histories in forms designed not to purvey but to hide the
truth. However, my colleague's point has relevance here, although I do not know

05:51.520 --> 06:00.420
that he would share the truth as I see it. Poul, for instance, often does not.
The relevance lies in the essence of the difference between fact and truth. A

06:00.420 --> 06:10.880
fact is an idea or an understanding which corresponds to reality in the outside
world. Truth is that which corresponds to our own conceptions of the universe.

06:11.120 --> 06:22.160
This is the appeal science fiction has for many of us, and also why many people
find it weird. Often they prefer out-and-out fantasy, such as in normal

06:22.160 --> 06:31.840
mainstream fiction, which accords with the truths that normal zombies of our
culture are supposed to accept. Even they know it to be unreal and escapist. And

06:31.840 --> 06:41.060
science fiction is no less so but at least we don't try to pretend it's real.
Then we can use it to convey truths as well as to hide through facts. As Randall

06:41.060 --> 06:54.600
Garrett maintained that a past fan can mention at San Francisco Airport science
fiction and mythologies have much in common. Back in February 1976 I did a

