11:23.900 --> 11:32.320
fiction. Of course, they were always important, in that the way they were
handled or not handled made the difference between a good story and a not-so

11:32.320 --> 11:43.900
-good story. Such elements are usually referred to as background, and character
development, and plot handling, or plot the luck, and various other aspects of

11:43.900 --> 11:54.020
storytelling itself. And they were what makes 20,000 Leagues Under the Sea a
supreme masterpiece, and Mysterious Island, its sequel, just a moderately good

11:54.020 --> 12:02.440
adventure to it. John Campbell is often given credit for introducing them into
science fiction, but they were certainly present in Food of the Gods and Tars

12:02.440 --> 12:12.560
Tarkas' Revolution, Antharchian Morals, to say nothing of Ralph 1. Du Forseffro
and Blish. The reason Campbell gets such credit is mostly because so many writers

12:12.560 --> 12:22.280
remember that Campbell was paying a cent a word and sometimes two cents for stories
which had some of these features, while Fred Pohl and his fellow unfortunates on

12:22.280 --> 12:32.280
other pulps were paying from a fifth to half a cent for stories that didn't.
What they don't stop to think about is that Campbell knew about these things

12:33.740 --> 12:44.580
because Harry Bates, paying two cents a word, and F. Orland Tremaine paying one
cent, had previously demanded it of Campbell. You may object that most of John

12:44.580 --> 12:51.780
Campbell Jr.'s own stories didn't have much in the way of character development,
but each of them did have something in the field of social or behavioral

12:51.780 --> 13:00.380
science, even if social and behavioral scientists might disagree with what he
did. The readers didn't want any better. As a matter of fact, they mostly agreed

13:00.380 --> 13:09.540
with him. The difference now is that with people like Ursula Le Guin and
McCaffrey writing, the standards for treatment of social and behavioral sciences

13:09.540 --> 13:19.140
and science fiction should now be at a higher level than the personal prejudices
of John Campbell and Ben Bova, or, for that matter, Jerry Pournelle. There are

13:19.140 --> 13:28.400
certain things we do know about people. We know that people tend to act in what
they consider to be their own best interests. And we know that this includes

13:28.400 --> 13:36.540
being able afterwards to live with their consciences. We know that people tend
to want to reciprocate what they get from others. This includes revenge as much

13:36.540 --> 13:46.140
as it includes paying other obligations. We know that, on the other hand, that
people tend to want to take things which are denied to them, but that they can

13:46.140 --> 13:54.840
be taught not to do this. We know that some people are capable of great cruelty
to others, and that other people raised in much the same cultures do not approve

13:54.840 --> 14:04.380
of this. There are many different kinds of behavior which anthropologists refer
to as war, but some peoples do not have any such behaviors, and many people

14:04.380 --> 14:14.600
refuse to take part in them. Many people write and talk about aggressive drives,
but one thing we do know is that aggression is not a separate drive, but that

14:14.600 --> 14:25.140
the word is a cover term for various behaviors engaged in for various reasons
when, but not always when, any drive or desire is interfered with it. We also

14:25.140 --> 14:34.460
know that such aggressive urge can be inhibited and then may or may not turn
against other targets, from the person himself to perfect strangers seen only at

14:34.460 --> 14:43.360
a distance. People who live in excessively polite cultures tend to be
excessively vicious in wars or in personal killings. We know that the basic

14:43.360 --> 14:52.720
relationships between people are power-mediated relationships, and that power,
and hence aggressiveness, is behavior related to control of access to resources.

14:53.360 --> 15:02.700
We know that dominance and submission are power relations and hence also involve
such control and lack of control, but that also dominance is itself a very

15:02.700 --> 15:12.560
prized resource, since a resource is anything anyone needs or wants or can be
fond into thinking he should try for. The various commodities, for instance,

15:12.720 --> 15:22.140
which are offered by those who conduct our practices of religion, are at times,
and for many people, very valuable resources. Information is a most important

15:22.140 --> 15:31.620
resource, and those who control access to it can be very powerful. It should be
noted that often, the actual practitioners in its supply do not control either

15:31.620 --> 15:42.240
the access or the supply. In our culture, this is what advertising and
publishing are concerned with. Because social relationships are power

15:42.240 --> 15:51.140
relationships, and the resources required and available depend on the
technology, and not only the technological level, but the technological biases

15:51.140 --> 16:03.720
of the states of the arts, technology is very important to social organization.
However, rapid technological change may not bring social changes so rapidly. The

16:03.720 --> 16:12.460
various fascist movements, for instance were efforts to reestablish feudal
social relationships in a period of industrial capitalism And as Milavon Giles

16:12.460 --> 16:21.220
pointed out in the book that got him in jail the first time the communist and
socialist revolutions were efforts to establish industrial technology in

16:21.220 --> 16:31.500
countries whose prevailing social structures were still feudal and colonial For
these reasons, plus those mentioned by James Gunn in This Fortress World I'm

16:31.500 --> 16:40.840
