possibility in the weapons shop universe. Doc Smith's civilization is even more

16:40.840 --> 16:52.780
convincing. As to Blish's fascist future, and I've already mentioned why not,
the substrate culture is now gone. To make a good story, you have to create

16:52.780 --> 17:02.460
tensions in the reader. Violence is a most inadequate way to do this, and
besides, it creates in the reader or viewer the erroneous belief that violence

17:02.460 --> 17:14.360
is fun and that violence solves problems. Also, as Ben Bovo points out in Notes
to a science fiction writer, slam-bang action is not what we mean by conflict.

17:15.460 --> 17:24.080
In science fiction, the main conflicts, that is to say, the tension-producing
situations, are simply culture shock and future shock, especially the

17:24.080 --> 17:34.120
explorations of extrapolations like Age Gold encourages writers to do for Galaxy
and the various worlds created, for instance, by Ursula Le Guin. These are

17:34.120 --> 17:43.860
wholly social and behavioral problems within the spectator himself being
operated upon by what he sees in the story. One thing I liked very much about

17:43.860 --> 17:53.020
John Campbell's A Post to Stories was his violation of one rule of American
storytelling. Our culture places great emphasis on failure. The object of

17:53.020 --> 18:02.340
competition and testing is not to produce winners, is to produce losers. And
thus, a general rule of our fiction is that a protagonist has to go through a

18:02.340 --> 18:11.560
cycle of degradation. He's not allowed to win until he's had a few failures.
John Campbell wasn't interested in this. He was interested in winners. His writers

18:11.560 --> 18:20.980
